Screen-time and sleep trackers

Recommended Screen TIme Guidelines
Based on guidance from the American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) and Common Sense Media:
Children & teens (6-18 years): aim for no more than 1-2 hours per day of recreational screen time
Healthy Screen Time Tips:
Set screen-free zones (at meal time, in bedrooms)
Establish consistent rules for daily screen use
Use built-in tools (like Screen TIme or Digital Wellbeing) to monitor and set limits
Encourage time for non-screen activities (outdoor play, reading, etc)
Talk Regularly with Children about what they watch or play
Model healthy screen use as an adult

üïíScreen-Time Tracker
What is it: A simple daily or weekly log where students or families can track how much time is spent on:
Social media
Gaming
Watching videos
Schoolwork or learning apps

How to use it:
Use the tracker for a few days to notice patterns
Talk about what feels ‚Äújust right‚Äù vs ‚Äútoo much‚Äù
Try one small change (like no screens for 30 mins before bed)

Recommended Sleep Guidelines
Based on recommendations from the CDC and the National Sleep Foundation:
Children 6-12 years: 9-12 hours per night
Teenagers 13-18 years: 8-10 hours per night

Tips for better Sleep:
Stick to a consistent bedtime and wake time, even on weekends
Avoid screens 30-60 mins before bedtime
Create a relaxing bedtime routine (reading, deep breathing, listening to calming music)




üåô Sleep Tracker

What it is: A basic chart to track bedtime, wake time, and total sleep each night. Includes space to write down how you felt during the day (tired, alert, calm, etc)

How to use it:
Fill it out each morning or night as quick check-in
Look for trends ‚Üí do you feel better on days you sleep more?
Try small changes, like dimming lights earlier or putting phones away before bed

Tips for Families
Make it a no pressure conversation
Celebrate small wins, like getting an extra 30 mins of rest
Consider a family ‚Äúscreen break‚Äù time where everyone puts devices away together

