Device-Level Parental Controls


Description: (for families using iOS 17/18, last updated June 2025)
This walkthrough shows parents how to add a child to Family Sharing, switch on Screen Time, and lock down nine key safety settings‚ÄîDowntime, App Limits, Communication Limits, Always Allowed apps, Content & Privacy Restrictions, Ask to Buy, Communication Safety, and Screen Distance.
iOS 17
STEP 1 ¬∑ ADD CHILD TO FAMILY SHARING‚ÄÉ [Insert Screenshot Step1] (Image Credit: Apple) Video
On the parent iPhone, open Settings ‚Ä∫ Family.


Tap Add Member (or pick an existing child).


Follow the prompts to finish setup.

STEP 2 ¬∑ TURN ON SCREEN TIME & SET A PASSCODE‚ÄÉ [Insert Screenshots Step2] (Image Credit: iMore)
Go to Settings ‚Ä∫ Screen Time ‚Ä∫ (child) and tap Turn On Screen Time


Choose This is My Child‚Äôs iPhone.


Create a four-digit Screen Time passcode that‚Äôs different from the device unlock code.

STEP 3 ¬∑ SCHEDULE DOWNTIME‚ÄÉ [Insert Screenshot Step3] (Image Credit: iMore)
Still in Screen Time, tap Downtime ‚Ä∫ Scheduled.


Pick a start and end time (e.g., 9 PM‚Äì7 AM).


Toggle Block at Downtime so apps lock without the passcode.

STEP 4 ¬∑ SET APP LIMITS‚ÄÉ [Insert Screenshots E & F]
Tap Screen Time ‚Ä∫ App Limits ‚Ä∫ Add Limit.


Select categories (e.g., Social, Games) or individual apps.


Set a daily limit‚Äîsay, 1 hour‚Äîand tap Add.

STEP 5 ¬∑ CONFIGURE COMMUNICATION LIMITS‚ÄÉ [Insert Screenshot Step5] (Image Credit: idownloadblog.com)
Open Screen Time ‚Ä∫ Communication Limits.


Decide who the child can contact During Allowed Screen Time and During Downtime (e.g., Contacts Only).

STEP 6 ¬∑ CHOOSE ‚ÄúALWAYS ALLOWED‚Äù APPS‚ÄÉ [Insert Screenshot Step6] (Image credit: iphonelife.com)
Go to Screen Time ‚Ä∫ Always Allowed.


Keep vital utilities (Phone, Messages); remove browsers or games you don‚Äôt want accessible 24/7.


STEP 7 ¬∑ TURN ON CONTENT & PRIVACY RESTRICTIONS‚ÄÉ [Insert Screenshots Step7] (image credit: lifewire.com)
In Screen Time, toggle Content & Privacy Restrictions ‚Ä∫ On.


Key sub-menus to adjust:


Web Content ‚Üí Limit Adult Websites.


App Store Purchases ‚Üí In-App Purchases = Don‚Äôt Allow.


Allowed Apps ‚Üí Hide Safari or Mail if desired.

STEP 8 ¬∑ ENABLE ‚ÄúASK TO BUY‚Äù & BLOCK IN-APP PURCHASES‚ÄÉ [Insert Screenshot Step8] (image credit: apple.com)
Settings ‚Ä∫ Family ‚Ä∫ (child) ‚Ä∫ Ask to Buy ‚Üí toggle Require Purchase Approval.


Double-lock by setting In-App Purchases = Don‚Äôt Allow under Content & Privacy ‚Ä∫ App Store Purchases.

STEP 9 ¬∑ TURN ON COMMUNICATION SAFETY & SCREEN DISTANCE‚ÄÉ [Insert Screenshot Step9A and Step9B] (image credit: apple.com)
Screen Time ‚Ä∫ Communication Safety ‚Üí switch On to get nudity warnings in Messages.


On supported models, enable Screen Distance to remind kids not to hold the phone too close.
Android
Description: (for devices running Android 13/14 with Google Family Link, updated June 2025)
These steps show how to link a child‚Äôs phone with Family Link, use Digital Wellbeing tools, lock the Google Play Store, require purchase approval, and enable SafeSearch.
STEP 1‚ÄÇ¬∑‚ÄÇADD CHILD WITH GOOGLE FAMILY LINK‚ÄÉ [Insert Screenshot Step1] (image credit: internetmatters.org)
On the parent phone, install/open Google Family Link and tap Add child


Follow the prompts to create or link the child‚Äôs Google Account.


On the child phone, sign in with that account (Settings ‚Ä∫ Passwords & accounts).


STEP 2‚ÄÇ¬∑‚ÄÇTURN ON DAILY SCREEN-TIME LIMITS‚ÄÉ [Insert Screenshot Step2 and step 2b] (image credit: androidcentral.com)
In the Family Link parent app, select your child ‚ûú Screen time.


Tap Daily Limit ‚ûú set total hours allowed (e.g., 2 h).


Optional: tap Lock device now to enforce limits immediately.


STEP 3‚ÄÇ¬∑‚ÄÇSET A BEDTIME (DEVICE ‚ÄúCURFEW‚Äù)‚ÄÉ [Insert Screenshot step 3] (image credit: androidcentral.com)
Same Screen time menu ‚ûú Bedtime.


Choose start/end times (e.g., 9 PM‚Äì7 AM). Device locks outside these hours.


STEP 4‚ÄÇ¬∑‚ÄÇADD PER-APP TIMERS WITH DIGITAL WELLBEING‚ÄÉ [Insert https://www.youtube.com/shorts/2TdrP8IFPP4]
On the child phone, open Settings ‚Ä∫ Digital Wellbeing & Parental controls.


Tap the pie chart, choose an app ‚ûú Set timer ‚ûú pick daily minutes (e.g., 30 m).


STEP 5‚ÄÇ¬∑‚ÄÇTURN ON BEDTIME MODE (SCREEN DIMS & MUTES)‚ÄÉ [Insert Screenshot step 4] (image credit: www.airdroid.com)
Settings ‚Ä∫ Digital Wellbeing & Parental controls ‚Ä∫ Bedtime mode ‚Ä∫ Customize.


Schedule it for sleep hours; enable Keep screen dark and Do Not Disturb.


STEP 6‚ÄÇ¬∑‚ÄÇUSE FOCUS MODE FOR HOMEWORK‚ÄÉ [Insert Screenshot step5] (image credit: www.pcmag.com)
Settings ‚Ä∫ Digital Wellbeing ‚Ä∫ Focus mode.


Select distracting apps to pause; tap Turn on now or set an automatic schedule.


STEP 7‚ÄÇ¬∑‚ÄÇLOCK GOOGLE PLAY WITH CONTENT FILTERS‚ÄÉ [Insert Screenshot G]
In the Family Link app ‚ûú choose child ‚ûú Controls ‚Ä∫ Google Play.


Pick Apps & Games, Movies, Books, etc., then set age ratings (e.g., ‚ÄúTeen‚Äù).


You‚Äôll be asked to create a PIN so kids can‚Äôt change the filters.


STEP 8‚ÄÇ¬∑‚ÄÇREQUIRE PARENT APPROVAL FOR PURCHASES‚ÄÉ [Insert Screenshot H]
Family Link ‚ûú child ‚ûú Controls ‚Ä∫ Google Play ‚Ä∫ Purchase approvals.


Set All content so every paid download or in-app purchase needs the parent‚Äôs OK.


STEP 9‚ÄÇ¬∑‚ÄÇENABLE OR LOCK SafeSearch IN CHROME & GOOGLE APP‚ÄÉ [Insert Screenshot I]
Family Link ‚ûú child ‚ûú Controls ‚Ä∫ Google Search.


Make sure SafeSearch = Filter; Family Link locks this setting for under-13s by default.


STEP 10‚ÄÇ¬∑‚ÄÇOPTIONAL: VIEW LOCATION & DEVICE INFO‚ÄÉ [Insert Screenshot J]
In Family Link, tap Location to see the child phone on a map or play a sound. Settings can be toggled per family preference. (No citation needed‚Äîfeature built into Family Link home screen.)

For additional levels of safety you can go into the individual apps and set parental controls there.


üéµStudent Safe Playlist Builder üéß
Build a Playlist that keeps your head and heart in a good place. The music we listen to can influence how we feel, how we act, and how we cope. This page helps you choose songs that are fun, inspiring, and safe, especially when life gets stressful.

For Students
Why Music Matters
Music can boost your energy, calm your nerves, or help you focus
Some lyrics and sounds can also trigger sad or anxious feelings
You deserve music that supports your wellbeing
How to Build a Safe Playlist
‚úÖ Choose songs that make you feel strong, peaceful, or positive
‚úÖ Pick music that helps you focus, relax, or express yourself
üö´ Avoid songs that leave you feeling angry, overwhelmed, or hopeless
Prompts to Help You Get Started
A song that makes you smile
A song that reminds you you're not alone
A song that helps you feel calm
A song that motivates you to keep going
For Parents & Caregivers
How You Can Help
Ask your child about the music they‚Äôre into without judgment.
Listen to a few songs together and talk about how they make you feel.
Encourage playlists that support your child‚Äôs resilience and wellbeing.
Red Flags in Media Content
Be aware of repeated themes like:
Hopelessness or self-harm
Glorification of violence or substance use
Isolation or extreme emotional swings

